			<a name="design"><h3>Design</h3></a>
			<p>
				In redesigning the new Express Setup, I addressed the issues encountered by new users, and aimed to make the new version easier, clearer, and more engaging in order to encourage self-setup.
			</p>
			<h4>PROBLEM: Users found the setup long and tedious.</h4>
			<p>
				On average, users would take over three hours to complete the flow, sometimes even a few weeks if they were waiting for an appointment with a live implementation representative. This often resulted in frustration or complete abandonment of the process.
			</p>
			<figure>
				<img src="/images/projects/express-project/5-ezgif.com-gif-maker.gif.gif" class="gif-width">
				<figcaption class="figure-caption text-xs-center gif-caption">Each section of the flow contained nested sections that required additional clicks and fields that users felt were unnecessary in what was supposed to be a quick setup.</figcaption>
			</figure>

			<h4>SOLUTION #1: Shorten the whole process.</h4>
			<p>
				To help a new user get set up as quickly as possible, I streamlined the flow and eliminated any step unrelating to getting a new phone number activated and ringing. In order to manage expectations, I used a new layout that presented all the steps visibly on one screen so that upon arrival, a user could immediately see what was required to complete the setup. The new design enabled users to complete the entire setup in under 15 minutes.
			</p>
			<img src="/images/projects/express-project/6-3step-setup.png">

			<h4>SOLUTION #2: Reduce the number of choices.</h4>
			<p>
				New customers wanted to verify their information and did not want to spend time thinking about what to fill in. In response, I created and promoted a common, default option. Eliminating the number of choices for the user helped reduce decision fatigue, and presenting a “Skip This step” button allowed the user to get through the flow quickly but made available the option of coming back later to customize special settings.
			</p>
			<img src="/images/projects/express-project/7-Vm-greeting-New.png" class="image-bottom-margin">

			<h4>PROBLEM: Users were not able to complete the previous flow on their own.</h4>
			<p>
				New users going through Express Setup typically first tried to set themselves up through trial-and-error, but required assistance from a combination of online search, support articles, or forums. Due to either frustration or failure to complete their own setup, customers would end up calling the support team.
			</p>
			<img src="/images/projects/express-project/8-Company_Greeting_before.png">

			<h4>SOLUTION: Be the customer service representative.</h4>
			<p>
				In attempts to recreate the live assistance experience, I designed the interface to feel like the user was talking to a live representative who was friendly, warm, and down-to-earth. I solicited required information in a conversational tone by asking questions that helped educate the user on how that feature worked and helped provide context for the user. I asked the user one question at a time, and presented followup questions only relevant to the user’s answers.
			</p>
			<img src="/images/projects/express-project/9-Company-Greeting-New.png" class="image-bottom-margin">

			<h4>PROBLEM: Users found the previous flow confusing.</h4>
			<p>
				Many new users did not understand the content within each section, nor did they understand why they needed to work on a certain step at that moment. The previous version of Express Setup required the user to complete numerous blank fields with no introduction or explanation about the feature they were configuring.
			</p>
			<img src="/images/projects/express-project/10-seq_sim_old.png">
			
			<h4>SOLUTION #1: Explain with pictures.</h4>
			<p>
				For those who often scanned past text or didn’t understand certain words, I made required fields visual with explanatory diagrams. A common question for the support team was the difference between forwarding a call “simultaneously” versus “sequentially”. Explaining terms with visual diagrams helped users quickly understand the feature.
			</p>
			<img src="/images/projects/express-project/11-before-after_sim-seq.gif" class="gif-width-sim-seq">

			<h4>SOLUTION #2: Warm users up before they dive in.</h4>
			<p>
				Since users found tasks hard to understand and out of context, I provided a brief introduction before dropping them into a form of blank fields. I informed them of what they were about to do and why it was important for them to complete this section at this point. Furthermore, I changed the originally-complex and technical language to be more colloquial and user-friendly.
			</p>
			<img src="/images/projects/express-project/12-Users_Before.png">
			<img src="/images/projects/express-project/13-Users_new.png">
